# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: air-quality-law
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Acid rain has been shown to have adverse impacts on forests, freshwaters, soils, microbes, insects and aquatic life-forms.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] In ecosystems, persistent acid rain negatively affects tree bark, leaving trees more susceptible to environmental stressors such as drought, fire, solar radiation, frost and pest infestation.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Acid rain is also capable of detrimenting soil composition by stripping it of nutrients such as calcium and magnesium which play a critical role in plant growth and maintaining healthy soil.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] In terms of human infrastructure, acid rain also causes the peeling of paint, corrosion of steel structures, and weathering of stone buildings and statues as well as having impacts on human health.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Some governments, including those in Europe and North America, have made efforts since the 1970s to reduce the release of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxide into the atmosphere through air pollution regulations such as the US Clean Air Act and the EU Ambient Air Quality Directive.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] These efforts have had positive results due to the widespread research on acid rain starting in the 1960s and the publicized information on its harmful effects.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The main source of sulfur and nitrogen compounds that result in acid rain are anthropogenic, but nitrogen oxides can also be produced naturally by lightning strikes and sulfur dioxide is produced by volcanic eruptions.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Acid rain is rain with a pH less than 5.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] A variety of natural and human-made sources contribute to the acidity of precipitations.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] For example nitric acid is produced by electric discharges in the atmosphere such as in lightnings.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The usual anthropogenic sources of acid deposition are sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxide.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] They react with water (as does carbon dioxide) to give solutions with pH < 5.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Occasional pH readings in rain and fog water of well below 2.4 have been reported in industrialized areas.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Acid rain was first systematically studied in Europe in the 1960s, in the United States and Canada in 1970s, and in India in the late 1980s.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The corrosive effect of polluted, acidic air of London on limestone and marble was noted in the 17th century by John Evelyn, who remarked upon the poor condition of the Arundel marbles.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Since the Industrial Revolution, emissions of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxides into the atmosphere have increased.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] In 1852, Robert Angus Smith was the first to show the relationship between acid rain and atmospheric pollution in Manchester, England.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Smith coined the term "acid rain" in 1872.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] As soon as the 1960s, European scientists began widely observing and studying the phenomenon.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] In 1955 two Swedish scientists had already quoted that "the precipitation over Sweden as a whole is definitely more acid than the CO2 equilibrium alone would permit".
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] At first, the main focus in this research laid on local effects of acid rain.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Waldemar Christofer Brøgger was the first to acknowledge long-distance transportation of pollutants crossing borders from the United Kingdom to Norway.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Near a century later this problem was systematically studied by Brynjulf Ottar in the 1970s.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Ottar's work was strongly influenced by Swedish soil scientist Svante Odén, who had drawn widespread attention to Europe's acid rain problem in popular newspapers and wrote a landmark paper on the subject in 1968.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The earliest report about acid rain in the United States came from chemical evidence gathered from Hubbard Brook Valley; public awareness of acid rain in the US increased in the 1970s after *The New York Times* reported on these findings.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] In 1972, a group of scientists, including Gene Likens, discovered the rain that was deposited at White Mountains of New Hampshire was acidic.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The pH of the sample was measured to be 4.03 at Hubbard Brook.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The Hubbard Brook Ecosystem Study followed up with a series of research studies that analyzed the environmental effects of acid rain.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The alumina from soils neutralized acid rain that mixed with stream water at Hubbard Brook.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The result of this research indicated that the chemical reaction between acid rain and aluminium leads to an increasing rate of soil weathering.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Experimental research examined the effects of increased acidity in streams on ecological species.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] In 1980, scientists modified the acidity of Norris Brook, New Hampshire, and observed the change in species' behaviors.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] There was a decrease in species diversity, an increase in community dominants, and a reduction in the food web complexity.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] In 1980, the US Congress passed an Acid Deposition Act.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] This Act established an 18-year assessment and research program under the direction of the National Acid Precipitation Assessment Program (NAPAP).
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] NAPAP enlarged a network of monitoring sites to determine how acidic precipitation was, seeking to determine long-term trends, and established a network for dry deposition.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Using a statistically based sampling design, NAPAP quantified the effects of acid rain on a regional basis by targeting research and surveys to identify and quantify the impact of acid precipitation on freshwater and terrestrial ecosystems.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] NAPAP also assessed the effects of acid rain on historical buildings, monuments, and building materials.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] It also funded extensive studies on atmospheric processes and potential control programs.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] From the start, policy advocates from all sides attempted to influence NAPAP activities to support their particular policy advocacy efforts, or to disparage those of their opponents.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] For the US Government's scientific enterprise, a significant impact of NAPAP were lessons learned in the assessment process and in environmental research management to a relatively large group of scientists, program managers, and the public.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] In 1981, the National Academy of Sciences was looking into research about the controversial issues regarding acid rain, in particular the role of fossil fuel combustion.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] President Ronald Reagan dismissed the issues of acid rain until his personal visit to Canada and confirmed that the Canadian border suffered from the drifting pollution from smokestacks originating in the US Midwest.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Reagan honored the agreement to Canadian Prime Minister Pierre Trudeau's enforcement of anti-pollution regulation.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] In 1982, Reagan commissioned William Nierenberg to serve on the National Science Board.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Nierenberg selected scientists including Gene Likens to serve on a panel to draft a report on acid rain.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] In 1983, the panel of scientists came up with a draft report, which concluded that acid rain is a real problem and solutions should be sought.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] White House Office of Science and Technology Policy reviewed the draft report and sent Fred Singer's suggestions of the report, which cast doubt on the anthropic causes of acid rain.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The panelists revealed rejections against Singer's positions and submitted the report to Nierenberg in April.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] In May 1983, the House of Representatives voted against legislation controlling sulfur emissions.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] There was a debate about whether Nierenberg delayed the release of the report.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Nierenberg denied the saying about his suppression of the report and stated that it was withheld after the House's vote because it was not ready to be published.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] In 1991, the US National Acid Precipitation Assessment Program (NAPAP) provided its first assessment of acid rain in the United States.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] It reported that 5% of New England lakes were acidic, with sulfates being the most common problem.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] They noted that 2% of the lakes could no longer support Brook Trout, and 6% of the lakes were unsuitable for the survival of many minnow species.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Subsequent *Reports to Congress* have documented chemical changes in soil and freshwater ecosystems, nitrogen saturation, soil nutrient decreases, episodic acidification, regional haze, and damage to historical monuments.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Meanwhile, in 1990, the US Congress passed a series of amendments to the Clean Air Act.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Title IV of these amendments established a cap and trade system designed to control emissions of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxides.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Both these emissions proved to cause a significant problem for U.S. citizens and their access to healthy, clean air.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Title IV called for a total reduction of about 10 million tons of SO2 emissions from power plants, close to a 50% reduction.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Phase I began in 1995 and limited sulfur dioxide emissions from 110 of the largest power plants to 8.7 million tons of sulfur dioxide.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] One power plant in New England (Merrimack) was in Phase I.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Four other plants (Newington, Mount Tom, Brayton Point, and Salem Harbor) were added under other program provisions.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Phase II began in 2000 and affects most of the power plants in the country.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] On March 10, 2005, the EPA issued the Clean Air Interstate Rule (CAIR).
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] This rule provides states with a solution to the problem of power plant pollution that drifts from one state to another.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] CAIR will permanently cap emissions of SO2 and NOx in the eastern United States.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] CAIR hoped to reduce SO2 emissions in 28 eastern states and the District of Columbia by over 70% and NOx emissions by over 60% from 2003 levels.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] CAIR was replaced by the Cross-State Air Pollution Rule (CSAPR), as of 1 January 2015.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Overall, the program's cap and trade program has been successful in achieving its goals.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Since the 1990s, SO2 emissions have dropped 40%, and according to the Pacific Research Institute, acid rain levels have dropped 65% since 1976.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Conventional regulation was used in the European Union, which saw a decrease of over 70% in SO2 emissions during the same period.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] In 2007, total SO2 emissions were 8.9 million tons, achieving the program's long-term goal ahead of the 2010 statutory deadline.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] In 2007 the EPA estimated that by 2010, the overall costs of complying with the program for businesses and consumers would be $1 billion to $2 billion a year, only one-fourth of what was initially predicted.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Forbes says: "In 2010, by which time the cap and trade system had been augmented by the George W.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The term citizen science can be traced back as far as January 1989 to a campaign by the Audubon Society to measure acid rain, with 280 volunteers nationwide, all members of the Audubon Society, making a one-year commitment to collect and measure the pH of precipitation samples.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Canadian Harold Harvey was among the first to research a "dead" lake.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] In 1972, he and Richard Beamish documented the gradual deterioration of fish stocks in 60 lakes in Killarney Park in Ontario, which they had been studying systematically since 1966.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] In the 1970s and 80s, acid rain was a major topic of research at the Experimental Lakes Area (ELA) in Northwestern Ontario, Canada.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Researchers added sulfuric acid to whole lakes in controlled ecosystem experiments to simulate the effects of acid rain.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Because its remote conditions allowed for whole-ecosystem experiments, research at the ELA showed that the effect of acid rain on fish populations started at concentrations much lower than those observed in laboratory experiments.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] In the context of a complete food web, fish populations crashed earlier than when acid rain had direct toxic effects to the fish because the acidity led to crashes in prey populations (e.g. mysids).
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] As experimental acid inputs were reduced, fish populations and lake ecosystems recovered at least partially, although invertebrate populations have still not completely returned to the baseline conditions.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] This research showed both that acidification was linked to declining fish populations and that the effects could be reversed if sulfuric acid emissions decreased, and influenced policy in Canada and the United States.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] In 1985, seven Canadian provinces (all except British Columbia, Alberta, and Saskatchewan) and the federal government signed the Eastern Canada Acid Rain Program.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The provinces agreed to limit their combined sulfur dioxide emissions to 2.3 million tonnes by 1994.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The US-Canada Air Quality Agreement was signed in 1991.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] In 1998, all federal, provincial, and territorial Ministers of Energy and Environment signed The Canada-Wide Acid Rain Strategy for Post-2000, which was designed to protect lakes that are more sensitive than those protected by earlier policies.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Acid rain was first reported in Mumbai (then Bombay) in 1974.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Acid rain has been a reported cause of decrease in soil pH, especially in the northeast region, as well as the coastal regions of Karnataka, Kerala, Odisha, Bihar, and West Bengal.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The spread of acid rain over India was first studied by a team of researchers in 1989.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Increased risk might be posed by the expected rise in total sulphur emissions from 4,400 kilotonnes (kt) in 1990 to 6,500 kt in 2000, 10,900 kt in 2010 and 18,500 in 2020.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Damage to Taj Mahal is a popular example of acid rain's corrosive effect in India.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] India is the largest sulphur emitter, mostly from coal-fired power plants.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] On 11 July 2025, the Indian government changed its own rules, exempting most coal-fired power plants from installing technology to reduce sulphur dioxide (SO2) emissions, reversing a key environmental policy launched in 2015 to cut sulphur emissions.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] In China, concern about the possible effects of acid rain emerged later than in Europe and North America.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The first reports in the international literature regarding acid rain in China appeared in the 1980s.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] A major cause of acid rain in China is the extensive use of coal, which in 2004 accounted for 69% of the energy production.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] However, a great need still exists for better monitoring of the environmental situation in China to support policy development and follow-up on emission reduction measures.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The most important gas which leads to acidification is sulfur dioxide.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] However, emissions of nitrogen oxides (NOx) and ammonia which are further oxidized to form nitric acid are of increasing importance due to stricter controls on emissions of sulfur compounds and the near absence of control on acid rain gasses emitted by intensive farming.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] 70 Tg(S) per year in the form of SO2 comes from fossil fuel combustion and industry, 2.8 Tg(S) from wildfires, and 7–8 Tg(S) per year from volcanoes.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The principal natural phenomena that contribute acid-producing gases to the atmosphere are emissions from volcanoes.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Acid-producing gases are also created by biological processes that occur in wetlands and the oceans.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The major biological source of atmospheric sulfur compounds is dimethyl sulfide.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Nitric acid is also produced by electrical activity in the atmosphere such as lightning.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Despite its toxicity, and negative effects of low pH, nitric acid in rainwater is an important source of fixed nitrogen for plant life.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Acidic sulfate deposits associated with tephra have been detected in glacial ice thousands of years old in remote parts of the globe, suggesting that volcanism was the main agent of rain acidification before the Anthropocene.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The principal cause of present-day acid rain is sulfur and nitrogen compounds from human sources, such as coal-fired power stations, animal agriculture, fertilizers, steel mills, and motor vehicles.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Power plants account for a quarter of nitrogen oxides (NOx) and two-thirds of sulfur dioxide within the atmosphere.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Industrial acid rain is still a substantial problem in China and Russia and areas downwind from them.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] These areas all burn sulfur-containing coal to generate heat and electricity.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The problem of acid rain has not only increased with population and industrial growth, but has become more widespread.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The use of tall smokestacks to reduce local pollution has contributed to the spread of acid rain by releasing gases into regional atmospheric circulation; dispersal from these taller stacks causes pollutants to be carried farther, causing widespread ecological damage.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Often deposition occurs a considerable distance downwind of the emissions, with mountainous regions tending to receive the greatest deposition because of their higher rainfall and direct contact with long-distance transported clouds.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] An example of this effect is the low pH of rain which falls in Scandinavia.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Acid rain falls at a pH value of roughly 4, making it harmful to consume for humans, plants, microbes and animals.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] When these low pH levels fall in specific regions, they not only affect the environment but also human health.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] With acidic pH levels in humans comes hair loss, low urinary pH, severe mineral deficiency, constipation, and many cases of chronic disorders like fibromyalgia and basal-cell carcinoma.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Combustion of fuels and smelting of some ores produce sulfur dioxide and nitric oxides (NOx).
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] They are converted into sulfuric acid and nitric acid by photochemical reactions in the troposphere.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The detailed mechanisms depend on the presence water and traces of iron and manganese.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] A number of oxidants are capable of these reactions aside from O2, these include ozone, hydrogen peroxide, and oxygen.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Wet deposition of acids occurs when any form of precipitation (e.g. rain, snow, fog) removes acids from the atmosphere and delivers them to the Earth's surface.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] This can result from the deposition of acids produced in the raindrops or by the precipitation removing the acids either in clouds or below clouds.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Wet removal of both gases and aerosols are both of importance for wet deposition.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Acid deposition also occurs via dry deposition in the absence of precipitation.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] This can be responsible for as much as 20 to 60% of total acid deposition.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] This occurs when particles and gases stick to the ground, plants or other surfaces.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Acid rain has been shown to have adverse impacts on forests, freshwaters and soils, killing terrestrial and aquatic life-forms as well as causing damage to buildings and having impacts on human health.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Sulfuric acid and nitric acid have multiple impacts on aquatic ecosystems, including acidification, increased nitrogen and aluminium content, and alteration of biogeochemical processes.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Both the lower pH and higher aluminium concentrations in surface water that occur as a result of acid rain can cause damage to fish and other aquatic animals as well as to microbes and plants.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] At pH lower than 5 most fish eggs will not hatch and pH lower than 4 will kill adult fish.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] As lakes and rivers become more acidic, biodiversity is reduced, while it is less affected in regions where freshwater is naturally acid.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Acid rain has eliminated insect life and some fish species, including the brook trout in some lakes, streams, and creeks in geographically sensitive areas, such as the Adirondack Mountains of the United States.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] However, the extent to which acid rain contributes directly or indirectly via runoff from the catchment to lake and river acidity (i.e., depending on characteristics of the surrounding watershed) is variable.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The United States Environmental Protection Agency's (EPA) website states: "Of the lakes and streams surveyed, acid rain caused acidity in 75% of the acidic lakes and about 50% of the acidic streams".
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Lakes hosted by silicate basement rocks are more acidic than lakes within limestone or other basement rocks with a carbonate composition (i.e. marble) due to buffering effects by carbonate minerals, even with the same amount of acid rain.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Soil biology and chemistry can be seriously damaged by acid rain.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Some microbes are unable to tolerate changes to low pH and are killed.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The enzymes of these microbes are denatured (changed in shape so they no longer function) by the acid, with attending collapse in soil functions (e.g. decomposition).
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The hydronium ions of acid rain also mobilize toxins, such as aluminium, and leach away essential nutrients and minerals such as magnesium.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Soil chemistry can be dramatically changed when base cations, such as calcium and magnesium, are leached by acid rain, thereby affecting sensitive tree species, such as sugar maple (*Acer saccharum*).
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Impacts of acidic water and soil acidification on plants could be minor or in most cases major.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Most minor cases which do not result in fatality of plant life can be attributed to the plants being less susceptible to acidic conditions and/or the acid rain being less potent.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] However, even in minor cases, the plant will eventually die due to the acidic water lowering the plant's natural pH.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Acidic water enters the plant and causes important plant minerals to dissolve and get carried away; which ultimately causes the plant to die of lack of minerals for nutrition.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] In major cases, which are more extreme, the same process of damage occurs as in minor cases, which is removal of essential minerals, but at a much quicker rate.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Likewise, acid rain that falls on soil and on plant leaves causes drying of the waxy leaf cuticle, which ultimately causes rapid water loss from the plant to the outside atmosphere and eventually results in death of the plant.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Soil acidification can lead to a decline in soil microbes as a result of a change in pH, which would have an adverse effect on plants due to their dependence on soil microbes to access nutrients.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] To see if a plant is being affected by soil acidification, one can closely observe the plant leaves.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] If the leaves are green and look healthy, the soil pH is normal and acceptable for plant life.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] But if the plant leaves have yellowing between the veins on their leaves, that means the plant is suffering from acidification and is unhealthy.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Moreover, a plant suffering from soil acidification cannot photosynthesize; the acid-water-induced process of drying out of the plant can destroy chloroplast organelles.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Without being able to photosynthesize, a plant cannot create nutrients for its own survival or oxygen for the survival of aerobic organisms, which affects most species on Earth and ultimately ends the purpose of the plant's existence.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] It has been suggested that the collapse of photosynthesis linked to acid rain (caused by the emission of sulfur oxide from intense volcanism) could have contributed to the Permian-Triassic mass extinction.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Adverse effects may be indirectly related to acid rain, like the acid's effects on soil (see above) or the high concentration of gaseous precursors to acid rain.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] High altitude forests are especially vulnerable as they are often surrounded by clouds and fog which are more acidic than rain.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Plants are capable of adapting to acid rain.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] On Jinyun Mountain, Chongqing, plant species were seen adapting to new environmental conditions.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The affects on the species ranged from being beneficial to detrimental.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] With natural rainfall or mild acid rainfall, the biochemical and physiological characteristics of plant seedlings were enhanced.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] However, once the pH decreases below the threshold of 3.5, the acid rain can no longer be beneficial and begins to have negative affects.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Acid rain can negatively impact photosynthesis in plant leaves, when leaves are exposed to a lower pH, photosynthesis is impacted due to the decline in chlorophyll.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Acid rain also has the ability to cause deformation to leaves at a cellular level, tissue scaring and changes to the stomatal, epidermis and mesophyll cells.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Additional impacts of acid rain includes a decline in cuticle thickness present on the leaf surface.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Because acid rain damages leaves, this directly impacts a plants ability to have a strong canopy cover, a decline in canopy cover can lead plants to be more vulnerable to diseases.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Dead or dying trees (forest dieback) often appear in areas impacted by acid rain, although other factors such as drought stress linked to global warming cannot be excluded, too.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Acid rain causes aluminium to leach from the soil, posing risks to both plant and animal life.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Furthermore, it strips the soil of critical minerals and nutrients necessary for tree growth.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] At higher altitudes, acidic fog and clouds can deplete nutrients from tree foliage, leading to discolored or dead leaves and needles, with broadleaved species tending to be more sentitive than conifers.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] This depletion compromises the trees' ability to absorb sunlight, weakening them and diminishing their capacity to endure cold conditions.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Other plants can also be damaged by acid rain, but the effect on food crops is (or should be) minimized by the application of lime and fertilizers to replace lost nutrients.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] In cultivated areas, limestone may also be added to increase the ability of the soil to keep the pH stable through the buffering effect of calcium carbonate, but this tactic is largely unusable in the case of wilderness lands.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] When calcium is leached from the needles of red spruce, these trees become less cold tolerant and exhibit winter injury and even death.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Acid rain may also affect crop productivity by necrosis or changes to soil nutrients, which ultimately prevent plants from reaching maturity.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Acid rain has a much less harmful effect on oceans on a global scale, but it creates an amplified impact in the shallower waters of coastal waters.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Acid rain can cause the ocean's pH to fall, known as ocean acidification, making it more difficult for different coastal species to create their exoskeletons that they need to survive and escape predation.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] These coastal species link together as part of the ocean's food chain, and without them being a source for other marine life to feed off of, more marine life will die.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Coral's limestone skeleton is particularly sensitive to pH decreases, because the calcium carbonate, a core component of the limestone skeleton, dissolves in acidic (low pH) solutions.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] In addition to acidification, excess nitrogen inputs from the atmosphere promote increased growth of phytoplankton and other marine plants, which, in turn, may cause more frequent harmful algal blooms and eutrophication (the creation of oxygen-depleted "dead zones") in some parts of the ocean.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] However, some studies on intertidal zones point to the prominence of acid rain as a cause of the observed decline in algal species richness.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Acid rain can negatively impact human health, especially when people breathe in particles released from acid rain.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The effects of acid rain on human health are complex and may be seen in several ways , such as respiratory issues for long-term exposure and indirect exposure through contaminated food and water sources.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Exposure to air pollutants associated with acid rain, such as nitrogen dioxide (NO2), may have a negative impact on respiratory health.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Water-soluble nitrogen dioxide accumulates in the tiny lung airways (bronchioles), where it is transformed into nitric and nitrous acids, causing damage to the cells of the respiratory tract by various mechanisms.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Pneumonia caused by nitric acids directly damages the epithelial cells lining the airways, resulting in pulmonary edema.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Exposure to nitrogen dioxide also reduces the immune response by inhibiting the generation of inflammatory cytokines by alveolar macrophages in response to bacterial infection, and more particularly in smokers.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The pollutant further reduces respiratory immunity by decreasing mucociliary clearance in the lower respiratory tract, which results in a reduced ability to remove respiratory infections.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The effects of sulfur trioxide and sulfuric acid are similar because the former produces sulfuric acid when it comes into touch with the wet surfaces of your skin or respiratory system.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The amount of SO3 breath through the mouth is larger than the amount of SO3 breath through the nose.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] When humans breathe in sulfur trioxide, small droplets of sulfuric acid will form inside the body and enter the respiratory tract to the lungs depending on the particle size.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The effects of SO3 on the respiratory system lead to breathing difficulty in people who have asthma symptoms.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Sulfur trioxide also causes very corrosive and irritation on the skin, eye, and gastrointestinal tracts when there is direct exposure to a specific concentration or long-term exposure.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Consuming concentrated sulfuric acid has been known to burn the mouth and throat, erode a hole in the stomach, burns when it comes into contact with skin, make your eyes weep if it gets into them, and mortality.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] A 25 parts per million (ppm) maximum for nitrogen oxides (NOx) in working air has been set by the Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) for an 8-hour workday and a 40-hour workweek.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Additionally, OSHA has established a 5-ppm nitrogen dioxide exposure limit for 15 minutes in the workplace.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The not-to-exceed limits in the air, water, soil, or food that are recommended by US regulations are often based on levels that affect animals before being modified to assist in safeguarding people.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Depending on whether they employ different animal studies, have different exposure lengths (e.g., an 8-hour workday versus a 24-hour day), or for other reasons, these not-to-exceed values can vary between federal bodies.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The amount of sulfur dioxide that can be emitted into the atmosphere is capped by the EPA.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] This reduces the quantity of sulfur dioxide in the air that turns into sulfur trioxide and sulfuric acid.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Sulfuric acid concentrations in workroom air are restricted by OSHA to 1 mg/m3.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Moreover, NIOSH advises a time-weighted average limit of 1 mg/m3.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Acid rain can damage buildings, historic monuments, and statues, especially those made of carbonate rocks, such as limestone and marble.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Acids in the rain react with the calcium compounds in the stones to create gypsum, which then flakes off.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The effects of this are commonly seen on old gravestones, where acid rain can cause the inscriptions to become completely illegible.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Acid rain also increases the corrosion rate of metals, in particular iron, steel, copper and bronze.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Places significantly impacted by acid rain around the globe include most of eastern Europe from Poland northward into Scandinavia, the eastern third of the United States, and southeastern Canada.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Other affected areas include the southeastern coast of China (the Minnan Golden Triangle) and Taiwan.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Many coal-firing power stations use flue-gas desulfurization (FGD) to remove sulfur-containing gases from their stack gases.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] For a typical coal-fired power station, FGD will remove 95% or more of the SO2 in the flue gases.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] An example of FGD is the wet scrubber which is commonly used.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] A wet scrubber is basically a reaction tower equipped with a fan that extracts hot smoke stack gases from a power plant into the tower.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Lime or limestone in slurry form is also injected into the tower to mix with the stack gases and combine with the sulfur dioxide present.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The calcium carbonate of the limestone produces pH-neutral calcium sulfate that is physically removed from the scrubber.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] That is, the scrubber turns sulfur dioxide pollution into industrial sulfates.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] FGD gypsum is used in construction materials (e.g. concrete), and instead of natural gypsum it can be added to agricultural soils as a source of high-quality sulfur and calcium.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Fluidized bed combustion also reduces the amount of sulfur emitted by power production.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Vehicle emissions control reduces emissions of nitrogen oxides from motor vehicles, but measures are required to further reduce road transport emissions, more especially in Diesel vehicles.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Acid rain is now as severe a threat to the developing world, especially India and China, as it was earlier to some of the developed countries.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] International treaties on the long-range transport of atmospheric pollutants have been agreed upon by western countries for some time now.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Beginning in 1979, European countries convened in order to ratify general principles discussed during the UNECE Convention on Long-Range Transboundary Air Pollution.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The purpose was to combat long-range transboundary air pollution.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The 1985 Helsinki Protocol on the Reduction of Sulphur Emissions under the Convention on Long-Range Transboundary Air Pollution furthered the results of the Convention.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Results of the treaty have already come to fruition, as evidenced by emissions of particulate matter and sulphur dropping by 30-80% since 1990 in Europe and by 30-40% in North America.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The effectiveness of the Convention in combatting acid rain has inspired further acts of international commitment to prevent the proliferation of atmospheric pollution.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Canada and the US signed the Air Quality Agreement in 1991.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Most European countries and Canada signed the treaties.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Activity of the Convention on Long-Range Transboundary Air Pollution remained dormant after 1999, when 27 countries convened to further reduce the effects of acid rain.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] In 2000, foreign cooperation to prevent acid rain was sparked in Asia for the first time.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Ten diplomats from countries ranging throughout the continent convened to discuss ways to prevent acid rain.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Following these discussions, the Acid Deposition Monitoring Network in East Asia (EANET) was established in 2001 as an intergovernmental initiative to provide science-based inputs for decision makers and promote international cooperation on acid deposition in East Asia.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] In 2023, the EANET member countries include Cambodia, China, Indonesia, Japan, Laos, Malaysia, Mongolia, Myanmar, Philippines, South Korea, Russia, Thailand and Vietnam.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] In this regulatory scheme, every current polluting facility is given or may purchase on an open market an emission allowance for each unit of a designated pollutant it emits.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] Operators can then install pollution control equipment, and sell portions of their emission allowances they no longer need for their own operations, thereby recovering some of the capital cost of their investment in such equipment.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The intention is to give operators economic incentives to install pollution controls.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] However, ethical arguments have been opposed to the ongoing rise of emissions trading, focusing on commodification of the atmosphere, pricing that which should not be priced, or civic responsibility.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The first emissions trading market was established in the United States by enactment of the Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] The overall goal of the Acid Rain Program established by the Act is to achieve significant environmental and public health benefits through reductions in emissions of sulfur dioxide (SO2) and nitrogen oxides (NOx), the primary causes of acid rain.
[src:air-quality-law/acid-rain] To achieve this goal at the lowest cost to society, the program employs both regulatory and market based approaches for controlling air pollution.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] The achievement of these objectives requires an open management process which seeks to include past, present and future stakeholders.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] Adaptive management needs to at least maintain political openness, but usually aims to create it.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] Adaptive management must therefore be a scientific and social process.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] It must focus on the development of new institutions and institutional strategies in balance with scientific hypothesis and experimental frameworks (resilience.org).
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] Adaptive management can proceed as either passive or active adaptive management, depending on how learning takes place.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] Passive adaptive management values learning only insofar as it improves decision outcomes (i.e. passively), as measured by the specified utility function.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] In contrast, active adaptive management explicitly incorporates learning as part of the objective function, and hence, decisions which improve learning are valued over those which do not.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] In both cases, as new knowledge is gained, the models are updated and optimal management strategies are derived accordingly.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] Thus, while learning occurs in both cases, it is treated differently.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] Often, deriving actively adaptive policies is technically very difficult, which prevents it being more commonly applied.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] The use of adaptive management techniques can be traced back to peoples from ancient civilisations.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] For example, the Yap people of Micronesia have been using adaptive management techniques to sustain high population densities in the face of resource scarcity for thousands of years (Falanruw 1984).
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] In using these techniques, the Yap people have altered their environment creating, for example, coastal mangrove depressions and seagrass meadows to support fishing and termite resistant wood (Stankey and Shinder 1997).
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] The origin of the adaptive management concept can be traced back to ideas of scientific management pioneered by Frederick Taylor in the early 1900s (Haber 1964).
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] While the term "adaptive management" evolved in natural resource management workshops through decision makers, managers and scientists focussing on building simulation models to uncover key assumptions and uncertainties.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] Two ecologists at The University of British Columbia, C.S.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] Holling and C.J Walters further developed the adaptive management approach as they distinguished between passive and active adaptive management practice.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] Kai Lee, notable Princeton physicist, expanded upon the approach in the late 1970s and early 1980s while pursuing a post-doctorate degree at UC Berkeley.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] The approach was further developed at the International Institute for Applied Systems Analysis (IIASA) in Vienna, Austria, while C.S.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] In 1992, Hilbourne described three learning models for federal land managers, around which adaptive management approaches could be developed, these are reactive, passive and active.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] Adaptive management has probably been most frequently applied in Yap, Australia and North America, initially applied in fishery management, but received more broad application in the 1990s and 2000s.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] One of the most successful applications of adaptive management has been in the area of waterfowl harvest management in North America, most notably for the mallard.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] Adaptive management in a conservation project and program context can trace its roots back to at least the early 1990s, with the establishment of the Biodiversity Support Program (BSP) in 1989.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] BSP was a USAID-funded consortium of WWF, The Nature Conservancy (TNC), and World Resources Institute (WRI).
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] Its Analysis and Adaptive Management Program sought to understand the conditions under which certain conservation strategies were most effective and to identify lessons learned across conservation projects.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] When BSP ended in 2001, TNC and Foundations of Success (FOS, a non-profit which grew out of BSP) continued to actively work in promoting adaptive management for conservation projects and programs.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] The approaches used included Conservation by Design (TNC) and Measures of Success (FOS).
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] In 2004, the Conservation Measures Partnership (CMP) – which includes several former BSP members – developed a common set of standards and guidelines for applying adaptive management to conservation projects and programs.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] Applying adaptive management in a conservation or ecosystem management project involves the integration of project/program design, management, and monitoring to systematically test assumptions in order to adapt and learn.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] The concept of adaptive management is not restricted to natural resources or ecosystem management, as similar concepts have been applied to international development programming.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] This has often been a recognition to the "wicked" nature of many development challenges and the limits of traditional planning processes.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] One of the principal changes facing international development organizations is the need to be more flexible, adaptable and focused on learning.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] This is reflected in international development approaches such as Doing Development Differently, Politically Informed Programming and Problem Driven Iterative Adaptation.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] One recent example of the use of adaptive management by international development donors is the planned Global Learning for Adaptive Management (GLAM) programme to support adaptive management in Department for International Development and USAID.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] The program is establishing a centre for learning about adaptive management to support the utilization and accessibility of adaptive management.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] In addition, donors have been focused on amending their own programmatic guidance to reflect the importance of learning within programs: for instance, USAID's recent focus in their ADS guidance on the importance of collaborating, learning and adapting.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] This is also reflected in Department for International Development's Smart Rules that provide the operating framework for their programs including the use of evidence to inform their decisions.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] There are a variety of tools used to operationalize adaptive management in programs, such as learning agendas and decision cycles.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] Collaborating, learning and adapting (CLA) is a concept related to the operationalizing of adaptive management in international development that describes a specific way of designing, implementing, adapting and evaluating programs.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] 3. adapting strategically based on applied learning.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] CLA practices have tangible benefits; for instance, a recent study recently found that companies "which apply more data-driven and adaptive leadership practices perform better" when examined against those which focus less on those practices.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] CLA integrates three closely connected concepts within the organizational theory literature: namely collaborating, learning and adapting.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] There is evidence of the benefits of collaborating internally within an organization and externally with organizations.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] Much of the production and transmission of knowledge—both explicit knowledge and tacit knowledge—occurs through collaboration.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] There is evidence for the importance of collaboration among individuals and groups for innovation, knowledge production, and diffusion—for example, the benefits of staff interacting with one another and transmitting knowledge.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] The importance of collaboration is closely linked to the ability of organizations to collectively learn from each other, a concept noted in the literature on learning organizations.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] CLA has been linked to a part of USAID's commitment to becoming a learning organization.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] CLA represents an approach to combine strategic collaboration, continuous learning, and adaptive management.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] A part of integrating the CLA approach is providing tools and resources, such as the Learning Lab, to staff and partner organizations.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] The CLA approach is detailed for USAID staff in the recently revised program policy guidance.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] Adaptive management as a systematic process for improving environmental management policies and practices is the traditional application however, the adaptive management framework can also be applied to other sectors seeking sustainability solutions such as business and community development.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] Adaptive management as a strategy emphasizes the need to change with the environment and to learn from doing.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] Adaptive management applied to ecosystems makes overt sense when considering ever changing environmental conditions.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] The flexibility and constant learning of an adaptive management approach is also a logical application for organizations seeking sustainability methodologies.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] Businesses pursuing sustainability strategies would employ an adaptive management framework to ensure that the organization is prepared for the unexpected and geared for change.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] By applying an adaptive management approach the business begins to function as an integrated system adjusting and learning from a multi-faceted network of influences not just environmental but also, economic and social (Dunphy, Griffths, & Benn, 2007).
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] The goal of any sustainable organization guided by adaptive management principals must be to engage in active learning to direct change towards sustainability (Verine, 2008).
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] This "learning to manage by managing to learn" (Bormann BT, 1993) will be at the core of a sustainable business strategy.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] Sustainable community development requires recognition of the relationship between environment, economics and social instruments within the community.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] An adaptive management approach to creating sustainable community policy and practice also emphasizes the connection and confluence of those elements.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] A practical example of adaptive management as a tool for sustainability was the application of a modified variation of adaptive management using artvoice, photovoice, and agent-based modeling in a participatory social framework of action.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] This application was used in field research on tribal lands to first identify the environmental issue and impact of illegal trash dumping and then to discover a solution through iterative agent-based modeling using NetLogo on a theoretical "regional cooperative clean-energy economy".
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] This cooperative economy incorporated a mixed application of: traditional trash recycling and a waste-to-fuels process of carbon recycling of non-recyclable trash into ethanol fuel.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] This industrial waste-to-fuels application was inspired by pioneering work of the Canadian-based company, Enerkem.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] See Bruss, 2012 - PhD dissertation: Human Environment Interactions and Collaborative Adaptive Capacity Building in a Resilience Framework, GDPE Colorado State University.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] It is difficult to test the effectiveness of adaptive management in comparison to other management approaches.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] One challenge is that once a system is managed using one approach it is difficult to determine how another approach would have performed in exactly the same situation.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] One study tested the effectiveness of formal passive adaptive management in comparison to human intuition by having natural resource management students make decisions about how to harvest a hypothetical fish population in an online computer game.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] The students on average performed poorly in comparison to the computer programs implementing passive adaptive management.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] Collaborative adaptive management is often celebrated as an effective way to deal with natural resource management under high levels of conflict, uncertainty and complexity.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] The effectiveness of these efforts can be constrained by both social and technical barriers.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] In Colorado, USA, a ten-year, ranch-scale (2590 ha) experiment began in 2012 at the Agricultural Research Service (ARS) Central Plains Experimental range to evaluate the effectiveness and process of collaborative adaptive management on rangelands.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] The Collaborative Adaptive Rangeland Management or “CARM” project monitors outcomes from yearling steer grazing management on 10, 130 ha pastures conducted by a group of conservationists, ranchers, and public employees, and researchers.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] This team compares ecological monitoring data tracking profitability and conservation outcomes with outcomes from a “traditional” management treatment: a second set of ten pastures managed without adaptive decision making but with the same stocking rate.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] Early evaluations of the project by social scientists offer insights for more effective adaptive management.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] First, trust is primary and essential to learning in adaptive management, not a side benefit.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] Second, practitioners cannot assume that extensive monitoring data or large-scale efforts will automatically facilitate successful collaborative adaptive management.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] Active, long-term efforts to build trust among scientists and stakeholders are also important.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] Finally, explicit efforts to understand, share and respect multiple types of manager knowledge, including place-based ecological knowledge practiced by local managers, is necessary to manage adaptively for multiple conservation and livelihood goals on rangelands.
[src:air-quality-law/adaptive-management] Practitioners can expect adaptive management to be a complex, non-linear process shaped by social, political and ecological processes, as well as by data collection and interpretation.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Administrative law deals with the decision-making of administrative units of government that are part of the executive branch in such areas as international trade, manufacturing, the environment, taxation, broadcasting, immigration, and transport.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Administrative law expanded greatly during the 20th century, as legislative bodies worldwide created more government agencies to regulate the social, economic and political spheres of human interaction.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Civil law countries often have specialized administrative courts that review these decisions.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] In Brazil, administrative cases are typically heard either by the Federal Courts (in matters concerning the Federal Union) or by the Public Treasury divisions of State Courts (in matters concerning the States).
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] In 1998 a constitutional reform led by the government of President Fernando Henrique Cardoso introduced regulatory agencies as a part of the executive branch.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Since 1988, Brazilian administrative law has been strongly influenced by the judicial interpretations of the constitutional principles of public administration (Art.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] 37 of the Federal Constitution): legality, impersonality, publicity of administrative acts, morality and efficiency.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] In Chile, the President of the Republic exercises the administrative function, in collaboration with several ministries or other authorities with *ministerial rank*.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Each ministry has one or more under-secretaries that act through public service to meet public needs.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] There is no single specialized court to deal with actions against the administrative entities, but there are several specialized courts and procedures of review.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Administrative law in China was virtually non-existent before the economic reform era initiated by Deng Xiaoping.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Since the 1980s China has constructed a new legal framework for administrative law, establishing control mechanisms for overseeing the bureaucracy, and disciplinary committees for the Chinese Communist Party.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] In 1989, China established its Administrative Litigation Law, which provides an avenue for people to challenge government action.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] In 2014, it was amended to lower the burdens on those challenging administrative actions.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] In 1990, the Administrative Supervision Regulations (行政检查条例) and the Administrative Reconsideration Regulations (行政复议条例) were passed.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] The 1993 State Civil Servant Provisional Regulations (国家公务员暂行条例) changed the way government officials were selected and promoted, requiring that they pass exams and yearly appraisals, and introducing a rotation system.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] The three regulations have been amended and upgraded into laws.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] In 1994, the State Compensation Law (国家赔偿法) was passed, followed by the Administrative Penalties Law (行政处罚法) in 1996.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Administrative Compulsory Law was enforced in 2012.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] The General Administrative Procedure Law is underway.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] In France, there is a dual jurisdictional system with the judiciary branch responsible for civil law and criminal law, and the administrative branch having jurisdiction when a government institution is involved.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Most claims against the national or local governments as well as claims against private bodies providing public services are handled by administrative courts, which use the *Conseil d'État* (Council of State) as a court of last resort for both ordinary and special courts.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] The main administrative courts are the *tribunaux administratifs* and appeal courts are the *cours administratives d'appel*.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Special administrative courts include the National Court of Asylum Right as well as military, medical and judicial disciplinary bodies.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] The French body of administrative law is called "*droit administratif*".
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] French administrative law, the basis of continental administrative law, has had a strong influence on administrative laws in several other countries such as Belgium, Greece, Turkey and Tunisia.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] In Germany, administrative law (German: *Verwaltungsrecht*) includes all law that specifically governs the legal relationships between public authorities and private persons, and that is not more precisely described as constitutional law.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] It sets out the tasks, aims and powers, as well as the organization and procedure, for all public authorities (German: *Behörden*).
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] As a field of legal study, administrative law has been differentiated from other branches of public law since the late 19th century in Germany; the precise delimitations of "administration" as a concept, however, are in contention.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Administrative law defines all aspects of public administration in the modern German state, whose legal culture emphasizes private persons' subjective rights (also, pursuant to art.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] 19IV of the current German Constitution of 1949, such rights must be fully justiciable).
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] The final say on the interpretation of the law lies with the courts of administrative jurisdiction (German: *Verwaltungsgerichte*), and the law usually permits close judicial scrutiny of public authorities' exercise of discretion.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] German legal scholarship does not have an agreed-upon definition for public administration.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] In one sense, administration – more precisely, everything that is subject to administrative law – is conceptualized as being all state activity of a certain type (material definition of public administration).
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] There is some danger of circular reasoning, since the formal categorization of the organizational unit may, in turn, derive from some material conception of its function.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] This discussion is of seen as being of particular importance when considering the role of administrative law in maintaining the division of government powers.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] For this purpose, a traditional approach tries negatively to define administration by subtracting those operations of the state which cannot be called administration, namely law-making and adjudication.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Using this negative definition, though, requires law-making and adjudication to be defined first, and leaves some activities that are a poor fit for the term "administration", such as the cabinet government's political leadership decisions, within the bounds of the definition.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Positive definitions abound, but none has won out over the others, or been entirely convincing to scholars of German administrative law.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] 'special administrative law') – e.g. police law, urban planning law, or local government law.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] The is not a full codification of the generally applicable ground rules of German administrative law, since it mostly only determines the procedure to be followed by public authorities in the fulfillment of their tasks, rather than mandating the substance of public administration.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] The VwVfG is a federal law that only applies to administration carried out by the German federal authorities.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] All 16 German *Länder* have, however, enacted a Law on Administrative Procedure of their own that is nearly word-for-word identical with the federal VwVfG.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] The standard form of administrative is the *Verwaltungsakt* (administrative ordinance).
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Pursuant to VwVfG § 35, an administrative ordinance exists where: a public authority (1) issues any decree, decision, or other official measure (2), in a matter of public law (3), with immediate legal effects outside the administration (4), to put in place a rule for an individual case (5).
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] The law governing the adjudication of questions of administrative law before the courts of general administrative jurisdiction (German: *Verwaltungsgerichte*) is the Code on Administrative Courts (German: *Verwaltungsgerichtsordnung*, abbreviated VwGO), which was enacted in 1960.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] The VwGO also does not apply to the courts of special administrative jurisdiction over tax disputes (German: *Finanzgerichte*) or over social benefits disputes (German: *Sozialgerichte*).
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] In Italy, administrative law is known as *Diritto amministrativo*, a branch of public law whose rules govern the organization of the public administration and the activities of the pursuit of the public interest of the public administration and the relationship between this and the citizens.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Its genesis is related to the principle of division of powers of the State.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] The administrative power, originally called "executive", is to organize resources and people whose function is devolved to achieve the public interest objectives as defined by the law.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] In the Netherlands administrative law provisions are usually contained in the various laws about public services and regulations.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] There is however also a single General Administrative Law Act (*Algemene wet bestuursrecht* or Awb), which is a rather good sample of procedural laws in Europe.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] It applies both to the making of administrative decisions and the judicial review of these decisions in courts.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Another act about judicial procedures in general is the *Algemene termijnenwet* (General time provisions act), with general provisions about time schedules in procedures.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] On the basis of the Awb, citizens can oppose a decision (*besluit*) made by an administrative agency (*bestuursorgaan*) within the administration and apply for judicial review in courts if unsuccessful.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Before going to court, citizens must usually first object to the decision with the administrative body that made it.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] This procedure allows for the administrative body to correct possible mistakes themselves and is used to filter cases before going to court.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Sometimes, instead of *bezwaar*, a different system is used called *administratief beroep* (administrative appeal).
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] The difference with *bezwaar* is that *administratief beroep* is filed with a different administrative body, usually a higher ranking one, than the administrative body that made the primary decision.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] *Administratief beroep* is available only if the law on which the primary decision is based specifically provides for it.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] An example involves objecting to a traffic ticket with the district attorney (*officier van justitie*), after which the decision can be appealed in court.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Unlike France or Germany, there are no special administrative courts of first instance in the Netherlands, but regular courts have an administrative "chamber" which specializes in administrative appeals.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] In Sweden, there is a system of administrative courts that considers only administrative law cases and is completely separate from the system of general courts.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] This system has three tiers, with 12 county administrative courts (*förvaltningsrätt*) as the first tier, four administrative courts of appeal (*kammarrätt*) as the second tier, and the Supreme Administrative Court of Sweden (*Högsta Förvaltningsdomstolen*) as the third tier.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Migration cases are handled in a two-tier system, effectively within the system of general administrative courts.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Three of the administrative courts serve as migration courts (*migrationsdomstol*) with the Administrative Court of Appeal in Stockholm serving as the Migration Court of Appeal (*Migrationsöverdomstolen*), from which appeals may go to the *Högsta Förvaltningsdomstolen*.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] In Taiwan the recently enacted *Constitutional Procedure Act* (憲法訴訟法) in 2019 (former *Constitutional Interpretation Procedure Act, 1993*), the **Justices of the Constitutional Court** of Judicial Yuan of Taiwan is in charge of judicial interpretation.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] As of 2019, this council has made 757 interpretations.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] In Turkey, the lawsuits against the acts and actions of the national or local governments and public bodies are handled by administrative courts which are the main administrative courts.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] The decisions of the administrative courts are checked by the Regional Administrative Courts and Council of State.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Council of State as a court of last resort is exactly similar to Conseil d'État in France.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Administrative law in Ukraine is a homogeneous legal substance isolated in a system of jurisprudence characterized as: (1) a branch of law; (2) a science; (3) a discipline.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Generally speaking, most countries that follow the principles of common law have developed procedures for judicial review that limit the reviewability of decisions made by administrative law bodies.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Often these procedures are coupled with legislation or other common law doctrines that establish standards for proper rulemaking.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Administrative law may also apply to the review of decisions of so-called semi-public bodies, such as non-profit corporations, disciplinary boards, and other decision-making bodies that affect the legal rights of members of a particular group or entity.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] While administrative decision-making bodies are often controlled by larger governmental units, their decisions could be reviewed by a court of general jurisdiction under some principle of judicial review based upon due process (United States) or fundamental justice (Canada).
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Judicial review of administrative decisions is different from an administrative appeal.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] When sitting in review of a decision, the Court will only look at the method in which the decision was arrived at, whereas in an administrative appeal, the correctness of the decision itself will be examined, usually by a higher body in the agency.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] This difference is vital in appreciating administrative law in common law countries.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] The scope of judicial review may be limited to certain questions of fairness, or whether the administrative action is *ultra vires*.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Administrative Procedure Act and New York State law).
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Administrative law, as laid down by the Supreme Court of India, has also recognized two more grounds of judicial review which were recognized but not applied by English Courts, namely legitimate expectation and proportionality.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] The powers to review administrative decisions are usually established by statute but were originally developed from the royal prerogative writs of English law, such as the writ of mandamus and the writ of certiorari.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] In certain common law jurisdictions, such as India or Pakistan, the power to pass such writs is a Constitutionally guaranteed power.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] This power is seen as fundamental to the power of judicial review and an aspect of the independent judiciary.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] In the United States, many government agencies are organized under the executive branch of government, although a few are part of the judicial or legislative branches.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] In the federal government, the executive branch, led by the president, controls the federal executive departments, which are led by secretaries who are members of the United States Cabinet.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] The many independent agencies of the United States government created by statutes enacted by Congress exist outside of the federal executive departments but are still part of the executive branch.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Congress has also created some special judicial bodies known as Article I tribunals to handle some areas of administrative law.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] The actions of executive agencies and independent agencies are the main focus of American administrative law.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] In response to the rapid creation of new independent agencies in the early twentieth century (see discussion below), Congress enacted the Administrative Procedure Act (**APA**) in 1946.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Because the United States Constitution sets no limits on this tripartite authority of administrative agencies, Congress enacted the APA to establish fair administrative law procedures to comply with the constitutional requirements of due process.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Agency procedures are drawn from four sources of authority: the APA, organic statutes, agency rules, and informal agency practice.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Agencies can only act within their congressionally delegated authority, and must comply with the requirements of the APA.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] At the state level, the first version of the Model State Administrative Procedure Act was promulgated and published in 1946 by the Uniform Law Commission (ULC), in which year the Federal Administrative Procedure Act was drafted.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] It incorporates basic principles with only enough elaboration of detail to support essential features, therefore it is a "model", and not a "uniform", act.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] A model act is needed because state administrative law in the states is not uniform, and there are a variety of approaches used in the various states.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] The present version is the 2010 Model State Administrative Procedure Act (**MSAPA**) which maintains the continuity with earlier ones.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] The reason for the revision is that, in the past two decades state legislatures, dissatisfied with agency rule-making and adjudication, have enacted statutes that modify administrative adjudication and rule-making procedure.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] The American Bar Association's official journal concerning administrative law is the *Administrative Law Review*, a quarterly publication that is managed and edited by students at the Washington College of Law.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] The agricultural sector is one of the most heavily regulated sectors in the U.S. economy, as it is regulated in various ways at the international, federal, state, and local levels.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] Consequently, administrative law is a significant component of the discipline of agricultural law.
[src:air-quality-law/administrative-law] The United States Department of Agriculture and its myriad agencies such as the Agricultural Marketing Service are the primary sources of regulatory activity, although other administrative bodies such as the Environmental Protection Agency play a significant regulatory role as well.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Like surface tension, adsorption is a consequence of surface energy.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] In a bulk material, all the bonding requirements (be they ionic, covalent, or metallic) of the constituent atoms of the material are fulfilled by other atoms in the material.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] However, atoms on the surface of the adsorbent are not wholly surrounded by other adsorbent atoms and therefore can attract adsorbates.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The exact nature of the bonding depends on the details of the species involved, but the adsorption process is generally classified as physisorption (characteristic of weak van der Waals forces) or chemisorption (characteristic of covalent bonding).
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] It may also occur due to electrostatic attraction.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The nature of the adsorption can affect the structure of the adsorbed species.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] For example, polymer physisorption from solution can result in squashed structures on a surface.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Adsorption, ion exchange, and chromatography are sorption processes in which certain adsorbates are selectively transferred from the fluid phase to the surface of insoluble, rigid particles suspended in a vessel or packed in a column.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Pharmaceutical industry applications, which use adsorption as a means to prolong neurological exposure to specific drugs or parts thereof, are lesser known.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The word "adsorption" was coined in 1881 by German physicist Heinrich Kayser (1853–1940).
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The adsorption of gases and solutes is usually described through isotherms, that is, the amount of adsorbate on the adsorbent as a function of its pressure (if gas) or concentration (for liquid phase solutes) at constant temperature.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The quantity adsorbed is nearly always normalized by the mass of the adsorbent to allow comparison of different materials.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] A number of different isotherm models have been developed.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] where x is the mass of adsorbate adsorbed, m is the mass of the adsorbent, P is the pressure of adsorbate (this can be changed to concentration if investigating solution rather than gas), and k and n are empirical constants for each adsorbent–adsorbate pair at a given temperature.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The function is not adequate at very high pressure because in reality $x/m$ has an asymptotic maximum as pressure increases without bound.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] As the temperature increases, the constants k and n change to reflect the empirical observation that the quantity adsorbed rises more slowly and higher pressures are required to saturate the surface.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Irving Langmuir was the first to derive a scientifically based adsorption isotherm in 1918.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The model applies to gases adsorbed on solid surfaces.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] It is a semi-empirical isotherm with a kinetic basis and was derived based on statistical thermodynamics.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] It is the most common isotherm equation to use due to its simplicity and its ability to fit a variety of adsorption data.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The surface is energetically homogeneous, and adsorbed molecules do not interact.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] At the maximum adsorption, only a monolayer is formed.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Adsorption only occurs on localized sites on the surface, not with other adsorbates.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] These four assumptions are seldom all true: there are always imperfections on the surface, adsorbed molecules are not necessarily inert, and the mechanism is clearly not the same for the first molecules to adsorb to a surface as for the last.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The fourth condition is the most troublesome, as frequently more molecules will adsorb to the monolayer; this problem is addressed by the BET isotherm for relatively flat (non-microporous) surfaces.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The Langmuir isotherm is nonetheless the first choice for most models of adsorption and has many applications in surface kinetics (usually called Langmuir–Hinshelwood kinetics) and thermodynamics.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Langmuir suggested that adsorption takes place through this mechanism: $A_{\text{g}}+S\rightleftharpoons AS$ , where *A* is a gas molecule, and *S* is an adsorption site.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The direct and inverse rate constants are *k* and *k*−1.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] where P is the partial pressure of the gas or the molar concentration of the solution.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] For very low pressures $\theta \approx KP$ , and for high pressures $\theta \approx 1$ .
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The value of $\theta$ is difficult to measure experimentally; usually, the adsorbate is a gas and the quantity adsorbed is given in moles, grams, or gas volumes at standard temperature and pressure (STP) per gram of adsorbent.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Through its slope and *y* intercept we can obtain *v*mon and *K*, which are constants for each adsorbent–adsorbate pair at a given temperature.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] *v*mon is related to the number of adsorption sites through the ideal gas law.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] If we assume that the number of sites is just the whole area of the solid divided into the cross section of the adsorbate molecules, we can easily calculate the surface area of the adsorbent.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The surface area of an adsorbent depends on its structure: the more pores it has, the greater the area, which has a big influence on reactions on surfaces.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] where *i* is each one of the gases that adsorb.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] 1) To choose between the Langmuir and Freundlich equations, the enthalpies of adsorption must be investigated.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] While the Langmuir model assumes that the energy of adsorption remains constant with surface occupancy, the Freundlich equation is derived with the assumption that the heat of adsorption continually decrease as the binding sites are occupied.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The choice of the model based on best fitting of the data is a common misconception.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] 2) The use of the linearized form of the Langmuir model is no longer common practice.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Advances in computational power allowed for nonlinear regression to be performed quickly and with higher confidence since no data transformation is required.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Often molecules do form multilayers, that is, some are adsorbed on already adsorbed molecules, and the Langmuir isotherm is not valid.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] In 1938 Stephen Brunauer, Paul Emmett, and Edward Teller developed a model isotherm that takes that possibility into account.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Their theory is called BET theory, after the initials in their last names.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The derivation of the formula is more complicated than Langmuir's (see links for complete derivation).
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The key assumption used in deriving the BET equation that the successive heats of adsorption for all layers except the first are equal to the heat of condensation of the adsorbate.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The Langmuir isotherm is usually better for chemisorption, and the BET isotherm works better for physisorption for non-microporous surfaces.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] In other instances, molecular interactions between gas molecules previously adsorbed on a solid surface form significant interactions with gas molecules in the gaseous phases.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Hence, adsorption of gas molecules to the surface is more likely to occur around gas molecules that are already present on the solid surface, rendering the Langmuir adsorption isotherm ineffective for the purposes of modelling.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] This effect was studied in a system where nitrogen was the adsorbate and tungsten was the adsorbent by Paul Kisliuk (1922–2008) in 1957.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] To compensate for the increased probability of adsorption occurring around molecules present on the substrate surface, Kisliuk developed the precursor state theory, whereby molecules would enter a precursor state at the interface between the solid adsorbent and adsorbate in the gaseous phase.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] From here, adsorbate molecules would either adsorb to the adsorbent or desorb into the gaseous phase.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The probability of adsorption occurring from the precursor state is dependent on the adsorbate's proximity to other adsorbate molecules that have already been adsorbed.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] If an adsorbate molecule enters the precursor state at a location that is remote from any other previously adsorbed adsorbate molecules, the sticking probability is reflected by the size of the SD constant.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] As SD is dictated by factors that are taken into account by the Langmuir model, SD can be assumed to be the adsorption rate constant.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] However, the rate constant for the Kisliuk model (*R*') is different from that of the Langmuir model, as *R*' is used to represent the impact of diffusion on monolayer formation and is proportional to the square root of the system's diffusion coefficient.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] As can be seen in the formula, the variation of *K* must be isosteric, that is, at constant coverage.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] that is to say, adsorption is more exothermic than liquefaction.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The adsorption of ensemble molecules on a surface or interface can be divided into two processes: adsorption and desorption.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] If the adsorption rate wins the desorption rate, the molecules will accumulate over time giving the adsorption curve over time.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] If the desorption rate is larger, the number of molecules on the surface will decrease over time.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The adsorption rate is dependent on the temperature, the diffusion rate of the solute (related to mean free path for pure gas), and the energy barrier between the molecule and the surface.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The diffusion and key elements of the adsorption rate can be calculated using Fick's laws of diffusion and the Einstein relation (kinetic theory).
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] where A is the surface area (unit m2), C is the number concentration of the molecule in the bulk solution (unit #/m3), D is the diffusion constant (unit m2/s), and t is time (unit s).
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Further simulations and analysis of this equation show that the square root dependence on the time is originated from the decrease of the concentrations near the surface under ideal adsorption conditions.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Also, this equation only works for the beginning of the adsorption when a well-behaved concentration gradient forms near the surface.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Correction on the reduction of the adsorption area and slowing down of the concentration gradient evolution have to be considered over a longer time.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Under real experimental conditions, the flow and the small adsorption area always make the adsorption rate faster than what this equation predicted, and the energy barrier will either accelerate this rate by surface attraction or slow it down by surface repulsion.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Thus, the prediction from this equation is often a few to several orders of magnitude away from the experimental results.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The desorption of a molecule from the surface depends on the binding energy of the molecule to the surface and the temperature.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The typical overall adsorption rate is thus often a combined result of the adsorption and desorption.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Since 1980 two theories were worked on to explain adsorption and obtain equations that work.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] These two are referred to as the chi hypothesis, the quantum mechanical derivation, and excess surface work (ESW).
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] where "ads" stands for "adsorbed", "m" stands for "monolayer equivalence" and "vap" is reference to the vapor pressure of the liquid adsorptive at the same temperature as the solid sample.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The plot of $n_{ads}$ adsorbed versus $\chi$ is referred to as the chi plot.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] For flat surfaces, the slope of the chi plot yields the surface area.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Empirically, this plot was noticed as being a very good fit to the isotherm by Michael Polanyi and also by Jan Hendrik de Boer and Cornelis Zwikker but not pursued.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] This was due to criticism in the former case by Albert Einstein and in the latter case by Brunauer.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] This flat surface equation may be used as a "standard curve" in the normal tradition of comparison curves, with the exception that the porous sample's early portion of the plot of $n_{ads}$ versus $\chi$ acts as a self-standard.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Ultramicroporous, microporous, and mesoporous conditions may be analyzed using this technique.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Typical standard deviations for full isotherm fits including porous samples are less than 2%.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Notice that in this description of physical adsorption, the entropy of adsorption is consistent with the Dubinin thermodynamic criterion, that is the entropy of adsorption from the liquid state to the adsorbed state is approximately zero.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Adsorbents are used usually in the form of spherical pellets, rods, moldings, or monoliths with a hydrodynamic radius between 0.25 and 5 millimetres (0.0098 and 0.1969 in).
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] They must have high abrasion resistance, high thermal stability, and small pore diameters, which results in higher exposed surface area and hence high capacity for adsorption.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The adsorbents must also have a distinct pore structure that enables fast transport of the gaseous vapors.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Silica gel is a chemically inert, non-toxic, polar, and dimensionally stable (< 400 °C or 750 °F) amorphous form of SiO2.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] It is prepared by the reaction between sodium silicate and acetic acid, which is followed by a series of after-treatment processes such as aging, pickling, etc.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] These after-treatment methods results in various pore size distributions.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Silica is used for drying of process air (e.g. oxygen, natural gas) and adsorption of heavy (polar) hydrocarbons from natural gas.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Zeolites are natural or synthetic crystalline aluminosilicates, which have a repeating pore network and release water at high temperature.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] They are manufactured by hydrothermal synthesis of sodium aluminosilicate or another silica source in an autoclave followed by ion exchange with certain cations (Na+, Li+, Ca2+, K+, NH4+).
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The channel diameter of zeolite cages usually ranges from 2 to 9 Å.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The ion exchange process is followed by drying of the crystals, which can be pelletized with a binder to form macroporous pellets.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Zeolites are applied in drying of process air, CO2 removal from natural gas, CO removal from reforming gas, air separation, catalytic cracking, and catalytic synthesis and reforming.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Non-polar (siliceous) zeolites are synthesized from aluminum-free silica sources or by dealumination of aluminum-containing zeolites.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The dealumination process is done by treating the zeolite with steam at elevated temperatures, typically greater than 500 °C (930 °F).
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] This high-temperature heat treatment breaks the aluminum-oxygen bonds and the aluminum atom is expelled from the zeolite framework.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The term "adsorption" itself was coined by Heinrich Kayser in 1881 in the context of uptake of gases by carbons.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Activated carbon is a highly porous, amorphous solid consisting of microcrystallites with a graphite lattice, usually prepared in small pellets or a powder.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] One of its main drawbacks is that it reacts with oxygen at moderate temperatures (over 300 °C (572 °F)).
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Activated carbon can be manufactured from carbonaceous material, including coal (bituminous, subbituminous, and lignite), peat, wood, or nutshells (e.g., coconut).
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The manufacturing process consists of two phases: carbonization and activation.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The carbonization process includes drying and then heating to separate by-products, including tars and other hydrocarbons from the raw material, as well as to drive off any gases generated.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The process is completed by heating the material over 400 °C (750 °F) in an oxygen-free atmosphere that cannot support combustion.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The carbonized particles are then "activated" by exposing them to an oxidizing agent, usually steam or carbon dioxide, at high temperature.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] This agent burns off the pore-blocking structures created during the carbonization phase, and so they develop a porous, three-dimensional graphite lattice structure.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The size of the pores developed during activation is a function of the time that they spend in this stage.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Longer exposure times result in larger pore sizes.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The most popular aqueous phase carbons are bituminous based because of their hardness, abrasion resistance, pore size distribution, and low cost, but their effectiveness needs to be tested in each application to determine the optimal product.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Activated carbon is used for adsorption of organic substances and non-polar adsorbates and it is also usually used for waste gas (and waste water) treatment.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] It is the most widely used adsorbent since most of its chemical (e.g. surface groups) and physical properties (e.g. pore size distribution and surface area) can be tuned according to what is needed.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Its usefulness also derives from its large micropore (and sometimes mesopore) volume and the resulting high surface area.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Recent research works reported activated carbon as an effective agent to adsorb cationic species of toxic metals from multi-pollutant systems and also proposed possible adsorption mechanisms with supporting evidences.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The adsorption of water at surfaces is of broad importance in chemical engineering, materials science, and catalysis.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Also termed surface hydration, the presence of physically or chemically adsorbed water at the surfaces of solids plays an important role in governing interface properties, chemical reaction pathways, and catalytic performance in a wide range of systems.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] In the case of physically adsorbed water, surface hydration can be eliminated simply through drying at conditions of temperature and pressure allowing full vaporization of water.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The low cost ($200/ton) and high cycle rate (2,000 ×) of synthetic zeolites such as Linde 13X with water adsorbate has garnered much academic and commercial interest recently for use for thermal energy storage (TES), specifically of low-grade solar and waste heat.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Several pilot projects have been funded in the EU from 2000 to the present (2020).
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The basic concept is to store solar thermal energy as chemical latent energy in the zeolite.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Typically, hot dry air from flat plate solar collectors is made to flow through a bed of zeolite such that any water adsorbate present is driven off.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Storage can be diurnal, weekly, monthly, or even seasonal depending on the volume of the zeolite and the area of the solar thermal panels.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] When heat is called for during the night, or sunless hours, or winter, humidified air flows through the zeolite.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] As the humidity is adsorbed by the zeolite, heat is released to the air and subsequently to the building space.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] This form of TES, with specific use of zeolites, was first taught by John Guerra in 1978.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Typical adsorbents proposed for carbon capture and storage are zeolites and MOFs.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The customization of adsorbents makes them a potentially attractive alternative to absorption.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Because adsorbents can be regenerated by temperature or pressure swing, this step can be less energy intensive than absorption regeneration methods.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Major problems that are present with adsorption cost in carbon capture are: regenerating the adsorbent, mass ratio, solvent/MOF, cost of adsorbent, production of the adsorbent, lifetime of adsorbent.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] In sorption enhanced water gas shift (SEWGS) technology a pre-combustion carbon capture process, based on solid adsorption, is combined with the water-gas shift reaction (WGS) in order to produce a high pressure hydrogen stream.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The CO2 stream produced can be stored or used for other industrial processes.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Protein adsorption is a process that has a fundamental role in the field of biomaterials.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Indeed, biomaterial surfaces in contact with biological media, such as blood or serum, are immediately coated by proteins.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Therefore, living cells do not interact directly with the biomaterial surface, but with the adsorbed proteins layer.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] This protein layer mediates the interaction between biomaterials and cells, translating biomaterial physical and chemical properties into a "biological language".
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] In fact, cell membrane receptors bind to protein layer bioactive sites and these receptor-protein binding events are transduced, through the cell membrane, in a manner that stimulates specific intracellular processes that then determine cell adhesion, shape, growth, and differentiation.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Protein adsorption is influenced by many surface properties such as surface wettability, surface chemical composition, and surface nanometre-scale morphology.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Surfactant adsorption is a similar phenomenon, but utilising surfactant molecules in the place of proteins.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Combining an adsorbent with a refrigerant, adsorption chillers use heat to provide a cooling effect.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] This heat, in the form of hot water, may come from any number of industrial sources including waste heat from industrial processes, prime heat from solar thermal installations or from the exhaust or water jacket heat of a piston engine or turbine.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Although there are similarities between adsorption chillers and absorption refrigeration, the former is based on the interaction between gases and solids.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The adsorption chamber of the chiller is filled with a solid material (for example zeolite, silica gel, alumina, active carbon or certain types of metal salts), which in its neutral state has adsorbed the refrigerant.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] When heated, the solid desorbs (releases) refrigerant vapour, which subsequently is cooled and liquefied.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] This liquid refrigerant then provides a cooling effect at the evaporator from its enthalpy of vaporization.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] In the final stage the refrigerant vapour is (re)adsorbed into the solid.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] As an adsorption chiller requires no compressor, it is relatively quiet.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Portal site mediated adsorption is a model for site-selective activated gas adsorption in metallic catalytic systems that contain a variety of different adsorption sites.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] In such systems, low-coordination "edge and corner" defect-like sites can exhibit significantly lower adsorption enthalpies than high-coordination (basal plane) sites.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] As a result, these sites can serve as "portals" for very rapid adsorption to the rest of the surface.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The phenomenon relies on the common "spillover" effect (described below), where certain adsorbed species exhibit high mobility on some surfaces.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The model explains seemingly inconsistent observations of gas adsorption thermodynamics and kinetics in catalytic systems where surfaces can exist in a range of coordination structures, and it has been successfully applied to bimetallic catalytic systems where synergistic activity is observed.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] In contrast to pure spillover, portal site adsorption refers to surface diffusion to adjacent adsorption sites, not to non-adsorptive support surfaces.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The model appears to have been first proposed for carbon monoxide on silica-supported platinum by Brandt *et al.* (1993).
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] A similar, but independent model was developed by King and co-workers to describe hydrogen adsorption on silica-supported alkali promoted ruthenium, silver-ruthenium, and copper-ruthenium bimetallic catalysts.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The same group applied the model to CO hydrogenation (Fischer–Tropsch synthesis).
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Zupanc *et al.* (2002) subsequently confirmed the same model for hydrogen adsorption on magnesia-supported caesium-ruthenium bimetallic catalysts.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Trens *et al.* (2009) have similarly described CO surface diffusion on carbon-supported Pt particles of varying morphology.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The presence of the metal serves as a lower-energy pathway for gaseous species to first adsorb to the metal and then diffuse on the support surface.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] This is possible because the adsorbed species attains a lower energy state once it has adsorbed to the metal, thus lowering the activation barrier between the gas phase species and the support-adsorbed species.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Hydrogen spillover is the most common example of an adsorptive spillover.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] In the case of hydrogen, adsorption is most often accompanied with dissociation of molecular hydrogen (H2) to atomic hydrogen (H), followed by spillover of the hydrogen atoms present.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The spillover effect has been used to explain many observations in heterogeneous catalysis and adsorption.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Adsorption of molecules onto polymer surfaces is central to a number of applications, including development of non-stick coatings and in various biomedical devices.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Polymers may also be adsorbed to surfaces through polyelectrolyte adsorption.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Adsorption is the beginning of viral entry, which is the earliest stage of infection in the viral life cycle.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The next steps are penetration, uncoating, synthesis (transcription if needed, and translation), and release.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The virus replication cycle, in this respect, is similar for all types of viruses.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Factors such as transcription may or may not be needed if the virus is able to integrate its genomic information in the cell's nucleus, or if the virus can replicate itself directly within the cell's cytoplasm.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] The game of *Tetris* is a puzzle game in which blocks of 4 are adsorbed onto a surface during game play.
[src:air-quality-law/adsorption] Scientists have used *Tetris* blocks "as a proxy for molecules with a complex shape" and their "adsorption on a flat surface" for studying the thermodynamics of nanoparticles.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] This sense of "agricultural land" thus includes a great deal of land not devoted to agricultural use.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] The land actually under annually-replanted crops in any given year is instead said to constitute *sown land* or *cropped land*.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] "Permanent cropland" includes forested plantations used to harvest coffee, rubber, or fruit but not tree farms or proper forests used for wood or timber.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] Land able to be used for farming is called **cultivable land**.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] Farmland, meanwhile, is used variously in reference to all agricultural land, to all cultivable land, or just to the newly restricted sense of "arable land".
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] Depending upon its use of artificial irrigation, the FAO's "agricultural land" may be divided into irrigated and non-irrigated land.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] In the context of zoning, *agricultural land* or *agriculturally-zoned land* refers to plots that are permitted to be used for agricultural activities, without regard to its present use or even suitability.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] In some areas, agricultural land is protected so that it can be farmed without any threat of development.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] The Agricultural Land Reserve in British Columbia in Canada, for instance, requires approval from its Agricultural Land Commission before its lands can be removed or subdivided.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] Under the FAO's definitions above, agricultural land covers 38.4% of the world's land area as of 2011 and in 2023 4.80 billion hectares (ha), down 2 percent, or 0.07 billion ha, compared with 2000.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] In 2011 permanent pastures are 68.4% of all agricultural land (26.3% of global land area), arable land (row crops) is 28.4% of all agricultural land (10.9% of global land area), and permanent crops (e.g. vineyards and orchards) are 3.1% (1.2% of global land area).
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] In 2022, the global agricultural land area was 4.78 billion hectares (ha), down from 4.79 billion hectares in 2021.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] One-third of the total agricultural land was cropland (1.58 billion ha in 2021), which increased by 6 percent (0.09 billion ha).
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] In 2023 Asia had the largest share of the global cropland area in 2023 (37%), followed by the Americas (23%), Africa (20%), Europe (18%) and Oceania (2%).
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] Approximately 30% of global cropland and permanent meadows and pastures can be found in three countries; 12% of global permanent meadows and pastures belonged to China, 10% to Australia and 8% to the United States of America.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] Asia had the largest share of the global cropland area in 2021 (37 percent), followed by the Americas (24 percent), Africa (19 percent), Europe (18 percent) and Oceania (2 percent).
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] There were differences in cropland expansion in the different regions during this period – Oceania and Africa both had rapid growth in cropland area (33 percent and 27 percent), while Asia and the Americas had more moderate growth (4 percent and 2 percent).
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] The cropland area of Europe declined between 2000 and 2021 by 5 percent.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] As a result, the cropland area of Africa overtook that of Europe in 2018.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] Approximately 30 percent of global cropland and permanent meadows and pastures can be found in three countries.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] In 2021, 12 percent of global permanent meadows and pastures belonged to China, 10 percent to Australia, and 8 percent to the United States of America.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] For the same year, the largest share of global cropland was in India (11 percent), followed by the United States of America (10 percent) and China (8 percent).
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] Cropland area per capita decreased in all regions between 2000 and 2021 as population increased faster than the cropland area.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] The countries with the highest cropland area per capita are Kazakhstan, Australia and Canada, due to vast areas of land available.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] Globally, the total amount of permanent pasture according to the FAO has been in decline since 1998, in part due to a decrease of wool production in favor of synthetic fibers (such as polyester) and cotton.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] The decrease of permanent pasture, however, does not account for gross conversion (e.g. land extensively cleared for agriculture in some areas, while converted from agriculture to other uses elsewhere) and more detailed analyses have demonstrated this.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] 2015 found that in the United States cropland increased by 2.98 million acres from 2008 to 2012 (comprising 7.34 million acres (29,700 km2) converted to agriculture, and 4.36 million acres (17,600 km2) converted from agriculture).
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] Prices and rents for agricultural land depend on supply and demand.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] Prices/rents rise when the supply of farmland on the market reduces.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] Landholders then put more land on the market – causing prices to fall.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] Conversely, land prices/rents fall when the demand for agricultural land declines because of falls in the returns from holding and using it.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] The immediate triggers for falls in land demand might be reductions in the demand for farm produce or in relevant government subsidies and tax reliefs.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] Poor-quality farmland in France and Spain is sold at no lower than €10,000/ha.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] The average Russian farm measures 150 hectares (370 acres).
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] The most prevalent crops in Russia are wheat, barley, corn, rice, sugar beet, soy beans, sunflower, potatoes and vegetables.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] Russian farmers harvested roughly 85–90 million tonnes of wheat annually in the years around 2010.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] Russia exported most to Egypt, Turkey and Iran in 2012; China was a significant export market as well.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] The average yield from the Krasnodar region was between 4 and 5 tonnes per ha, while the Russian average was only 2t/ha.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] The Basic Element Group, a conglomerate owned by Oleg Deripaska, is one of Russia's leading agricultural producers, and owns or manages 109,000ha of Russian farmland, out of 90m actual and 115m total (0.12% actual).
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] In 2013, Ukraine was ranked third in corn production and sixth in wheat production.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] It was the main supplier of corn, wheat, and rape to Europe, although it is unclear whether the internal supply from countries like France were accounted in this calculation.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] Ukrainian farmers achieve 60% of the output per unit area of their North American competitors.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] UkrLandFarming PLC produces, from 650,000 hectares (1.6m acres), corn, wheat, barley, sugar beet, and sunflowers.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] Until 2014, the chief Ukrainian export terminal was the Crimean port of Sevastopol.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] Prime farmland in Illinois is valued, as of August 2018, at $26,000 a hectare.
[src:air-quality-law/agricultural-land] Average cropland value in the Midwest according to 2020 data from the US Department of Agriculture is $4,607 per acre (about $11,000 per hectare).
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] The **Air Pollution Control Act of 1955** (Pub.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] 322) was the first U.S. federal law to address the national environmental problem of air pollution.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] This was "an act to provide research and technical assistance relating to air pollution control".
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] The act "left states principally in charge of prevention and control of air pollution at the source".
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] The act declared that air pollution was a danger to public health and welfare, but preserved the "primary responsibilities and rights of the states and local government in controlling air pollution".
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] The act put the federal government in a purely informational role, authorizing the United States Surgeon General to conduct research, investigate, and pass out information "relating to air pollution and the prevention and abatement thereof".
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] Therefore, The Air Pollution Control Act contained no provisions for the federal government to actively combat air pollution by punishing polluters.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] The next Congressional statement on air pollution would come with the Clean Air Act of 1963.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] The Air Pollution Control Act was the culmination of much research done on fuel emissions by the federal government in the 1930s and 1940s.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] Additional legislation was passed in 1963 to better fully define air quality criteria and give more power in defining what air quality was to the Secretary of Health, Education, and Welfare.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] This additional legislation would provide grants to both local and state agencies.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] A replacement, the Clean Air Act (United States) (CAA), was enacted to replace the Air Pollution Control Act of 1955.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] A decade later the Motor Vehicle Air Pollution Control Act was enacted to focus more specifically on automotive emission standards.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] A mere two years later, the Federal Air Quality Act was established to define "air quality control regions" scientifically based on topographical and meteorological facets of air pollution.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] California was the first state to act against air pollution when the metropolis of Los Angeles began to notice deteriorating air quality.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] The location of Los Angeles furthered the problem as several geographical and meteorological problems unique to the area exacerbated the air pollution problem.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] Prior to the Air Pollution Control Act of 1955, little headway was made to initiate this air pollution reform.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] U.S. cities Chicago and Cincinnati first established smoke ordinances in 1881.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] In 1904, Philadelphia passed an ordinance limiting the amount of smoke in flues, chimneys, and open spaces.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] The ordinance imposed a penalty if not all smoke inspections were passed.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] It was not until 1947 that California authorized the creation of Air Pollution Control Districts in every county of the state.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] There have been several amendments made to The Air Pollution Act of 1955.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] The first amendment came in 1960, which extended research funding for four years.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] The next amendment came in 1962 and basically enforced the principle provisions of the original act.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] In addition, this amendment also called for research to be done by the Surgeon General.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] In 1967, the Air Quality Act of 1967 was passed.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] In 1967, the Air Quality Act was enacted in order to expand federal government activities.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] In accordance with this law, enforcement proceedings were initiated in areas subject to interstate air pollution transport.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] This amendment allowed states to enact federal automobile emissions standards.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] Senator Edmond Muskie (D-Maine) said that this was the “first comprehensive federal air pollution control.” The National Air Pollution Control Administration then provided technical information to the states, which the states used to develop air quality standards.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] The NAPCA then had the power to veto any of the states' proposed emission standards.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] This amendment was not as effective as it was initially thought to be, with only 36 air regions designated, and as well as no states having fully developed pollution control programs.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] In 1969, another amendment was made to the act.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] This amendment further expanded the research on low emissions, fuels, and automobiles.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] The 1970 amendments, also known as the Clean Air Act, completely rewrote the 1967 act.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] In particular, the 1970 amendments required the newly created The United States Environmental Protection Agency to set technology-based National Ambient Air Quality Standards for major new stationary sources and state air quality management programs to protect public health and welfare.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] In addition, the 1970 amendments required various states to submit state implementation plans for attaining and maintaining the National Ambient Air Quality Standards and required the use of air monitoring to determine if implementation plans were successful.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] National technology-forcing emissions standards were also set for new automobiles.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] This amendment allowed citizens the ability to sue polluters or government agencies for failure to abide by the act.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] Finally, the amendment required that by 1975, the entire United States would attain clean air status.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] 1990 was the most recent amendments to the act under President George H.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] The 1990 amendments granted significantly more authority to the federal government than any prior air quality legislation.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] Nine subjects were identified in this amendment, with smog, acid rain, motor vehicle emissions, and toxic air pollution among them.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] Five severity classifications were identified to measure smog.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] To better control acid rain, new regulatory programs were created.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] New and stricter emission standards were created for motor vehicles beginning with the 1995 model year.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] The National Emission Standards for Hazardous Air Pollutants program was created to expand much broader industries and activities.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] The first National Air Pollution Symposium in the United States was held in 1949 and hosted by Stanford Research Institute (now SRI International).
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] At first, smaller governments were responsible for the passage and enforcement of such legislation.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] The main purpose of the Air Pollution Control Act of 1955 was to provide research assistance to find a way to control air pollution from its source.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] A total of $5 million was granted to the public health service for a five-year period to conduct this research.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] According to a private website, the amount was $3 million allotted per year for the five-year period of research.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] This was the first act from the government that made U.S. citizens and policy makers aware of this global problem.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] Unfortunately, this act did little to prevent air pollution, but it at least made government aware that this was a national problem.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] The act allowed Congress to reserve the right to control this growing problem.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] The Air Pollution Control Act of 1955 was the first federal law regarding air pollution.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] This act began to inform the public about the hazards of air pollution and detailed new emissions standards.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] Public opinion polls showed that the percentage of Americans who regarded air pollution as a serious problem almost doubled from 28% in 1965 to 55% in 1968 with the addition of all the amendments made to the original Air Pollution Control Act of 1955.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] Despite having the term "control" in the title of the act, this legislation had no regulation component.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] In the early 1950s Congress did not want to interfere with states' rights; as such, the early laws of the act were not strong.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] This act set up the role that the government would play in research on air pollution effects and control.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] As such, the act was the forefront of the air pollution movement that continues to this day.
[src:air-quality-law/air-pollution-control-act-of-1955] Amendments were added to The Air Pollution Control Act of 1955 as well as the Clear Air Act frequently by the government, as the government continued to further research on the topic and improve air quality.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] The **Air Quality Agreement** is an environmental treaty between Canada and the United States.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] It was signed on 13 March 1991 by Canadian prime minister Brian Mulroney and American President George H.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] Bush and entered into force immediately.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] It was popularly referred to during its negotiations as the "**Acid Rain Treaty**", especially in Canada.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] The treaty aimed at reducing toxic air pollutants primarily responsible for causing acid rain, such as sulfur dioxide ( ${\ce {SO2}}$ ) and nitrogen oxide ( ${\ce {NOx}}$ ).
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] Negotiations began in 1986 when Mulroney first discussed the issue with then-president Reagan.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] In 1991 The United States and Canada signed a bilateral executive agreement aimed at reducing transboundary air pollution referred to as **The U.S.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] A bilateral agreement occurs when two parties, in this case two countries, undertake a mutual obligation to fulfill a set goal.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] Transboundary air pollution occurs when pollution created in one country negatively impacting another country.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] The bilateral agreement has three main objectives: reducing the impacts of transboundary pollution, prioritizing health and the environment, and corroborating to ensure each country is meeting its air quality standards.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] By signing the agreement, both countries concur that transboundary pollution could be mitigated through collaboration and cohesive actions.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] An Air Quality Committee was formed responsible for reporting progress every two years.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] In 2007, both parties successfully reached their targets outlined in the Acid Rain Annex and the Ozone Annex, demonstrating an overall emissions decrease and effective participation from both parties.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] The United States-Canada Air Quality Agreement initially prioritized the reduction of acid rain within each country.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] Established in 1991, the Acid Rain Annex aimed at reducing ${\ce {NOx}}$ and ${\ce {SO2}}$ , the main contributors of acid rain.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] The annex includes preventative measures aimed at minimizing declining air quality, visibility impairment, and actively monitoring emissions.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] Both countries independently sought to mitigate acid rain and its effects.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] Canada established the Eastern Canada Acid Rain Program in 1985 aimed at decreasing acid rain in Canada’s seven Eastern Provinces by 1994.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] By 1998 the Canadian Council of Ministers created the “Canada-Wide Acid Rain Strategy for Post 2000” a strategic plan set in place prioritizing human health and protecting sensitive communities affected by acid rain.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] The plan had four main elements: consistent reports to the public and the Ministers, reducing Sulphur Dioxide in the seven provinces, promoting continuous scientific research and monitoring, and preventive measures for non-affected areas.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] Canada is more vulnerable than the United States to acid rain, due to its geology and lack of compounds responsible for neutralizing acid deposition.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] Additionally, attributed to its downward position, Canada endures high levels of air pollution from the United States, with nearly fifty percent of pollution in Canada originating from the United States, further contributing to the formation of acid rain in Canada.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] The United States, in comparison, has few areas vulnerable to acid rain, with the regions being located mainly in the Northeastern regions near Canada.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] In 1995 the United States implemented the Acid Rain Program targeted at decreasing Sulphur Dioxide and Nitrogen Oxides.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] It went on to establish the first cap-and-trade program within the United States, the ${\ce {SO2}}$ Program, that set an ${\ce {SO2}}$ emissions cap on generating facilities.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] The Ozone Annex is a bilateral agreement added to the U.S.-Canada Air Quality Agreement and signed on December 7, 2000.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] Its purpose is to reduce transboundary pollution that pollutes the tropospheric ozone and creates smog, achieved by implementing air quality regulations and decreasing emissions.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] Early developments of the Ozone Annex occurred in 1997 after the both parties agreed scientific cooperation was required to address ground-level ozone and particulate matter.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] The specific pollution targeted by the treaty includes nitrogen oxide and volatile organic compounds, the most contributing factors to the formation of smog.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] The final draft of the agreement delineates particular areas within the countries where the Ozone Annex would be applied, referred to as the Pollutant Emission Management Area.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] In the United States this area includes eighteen different states, as well as the District of Columbia, roughly affecting 40% of the American population.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-agreement] In Canada, the annex particularly focused on Southern and Central Ontario and the Southern Quebec region, affecting nearly 50% of the Canada population.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Air quality regulation must identify the substances and energies which qualify as "pollution" for purposes of further control.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] While specific labels vary from jurisdiction to jurisdiction, there is broad consensus among many governments regarding what constitutes air pollution.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] For example, the United States Clean Air Act identifies ozone, particulate matter, carbon monoxide, nitrogen oxides (NOx), sulfur dioxide (SO2), and lead (Pb) as "criteria" pollutants requiring nationwide regulation.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] EPA has also identified over 180 compounds it has classified as "hazardous" pollutants requiring strict control.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Other compounds have been identified as air pollutants due to their adverse impact on the environment (e.g., CFCs as agents of ozone depletion), and on human health (e.g., asbestos in indoor air).
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] A broader conception of air pollution may also incorporate noise, light, and radiation.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] The United States has recently seen controversy over whether carbon dioxide (CO2) and other greenhouse gases should be classified as air pollutants.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Air quality standards are legal standards or requirements governing concentrations of air pollutants in breathed air, both outdoors and indoors.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Such standards generally are expressed as levels of specific air pollutants that are deemed acceptable in ambient air, and are most often designed to reduce or eliminate the human health effects of air pollution, although secondary effects such as crop and building damage may also be considered.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Determining appropriate air quality standards generally requires up-to-date scientific data on the health effects of the pollutant under review, with specific information on exposure times and sensitive populations.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] It also generally requires periodic or continuous monitoring of air quality.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Another set of standards, for indoor air in employment settings, is administered by the U.S.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Occupational Safety and Health Administration.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] A distinction may be made between mandatory and aspirational air quality standards.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] For example, U.S. state governments must work toward achieving NAAQS, but are not forced to meet them.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] On the other hand, employers may be required immediately to rectify any violation of OSHA workplace air quality standards.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Emission standards are the legal requirements governing air pollutants released into the atmosphere.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Emission standards set quantitative limits on the permissible amount of specific air pollutants that may be released from specific sources over specific timeframes.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] They are generally designed to achieve air quality standards and to protect human life.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Different regions and countries have different standards for vehicle emissions.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Numerous methods exist for determining appropriate emissions standards, and different regulatory approaches may be taken depending on the source, industry, and air pollutant under review.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Specific limits may be set by reference to and within the confines of more general air quality standards.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Specific sources may be regulated by means of performance standards, meaning numerical limits on the emission of a specific pollutant from that source category.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Regulators may also mandate the adoption and use of specific control technologies, often with reference to feasibility, availability, and cost.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Still other standards may be set using performance as a benchmark – for example, requiring all of a specific type of facility to meet the emissions limits achieved by the best performing facility of the group.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] All of these methods may be modified by incorporating emissions averaging, market mechanisms such as emissions trading, and other alternatives.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] For example, all of these approaches are used in the United States.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] The United States Environmental Protection Agency (responsible for air quality regulation at a national level under the U.S.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Clean Air Act, utilizes performance standards under the New Source Performance Standard (NSPS) program.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Technology requirements are set under RACT (Reasonably Available Control Technology), BACT (Best Available Control Technology), and LAER (Lowest Achievable Emission Rate) standards.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Flexibility alternatives are implemented in U.S. programs to eliminate acid rain, protect the ozone layer, achieve permitting standards, and reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] In place of or in combination with air quality standards and emission control standards, governments may choose to reduce air pollution by requiring regulated parties to adopt emissions control technologies (i.e., technology that reduces or eliminates emissions).
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Such devices include but are not limited to flare stacks, incinerators, catalytic combustion reactors, selective catalytic reduction reactors, electrostatic precipitators, baghouses, wet scrubbers, cyclones, thermal oxidizers, Venturi scrubbers, carbon adsorbers, and biofilters.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] The selection of emissions control technology may be the subject of complex regulation that may balance multiple conflicting considerations and interests, including economic cost, availability, feasibility, and effectiveness.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] The various weight given to each factor may ultimately determine the technology selected.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] The outcome of an analysis seeking a technology that all players in an industry can afford could be different from an analysis seeking to require all players to adopt the most effective technology yet developed, regardless of cost.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Air quality laws may take the form of bans.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] While arguably a class of emissions control law (where the emission limit is set to zero), bans differ in that they may regulate activity other than the emission of a pollutant itself, even though the ultimate goal is to eliminate the emission of the pollutant.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Residential and commercial burning of wood materials may be restricted during times of poor air quality, eliminating the immediate emission of particulate matter and requiring use of non-polluting heating methods.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] A more significant example is the widespread ban on the manufacture of dichlorodifluoromethane (Freon)), formerly the standard refrigerant in automobile air conditioning systems.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] This substance, often released into the atmosphere unintentionally as a result of refrigerant system leaks, was determined to have a significant ozone depletion potential, and its widespread use to pose a significant threat to the Earth's ozone layer.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Its manufacture was prohibited as part of a suite of restrictions adopted internationally in the Montreal Protocol to the Vienna Convention for the Protection of the Ozone Layer.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Still another example is the ban on use of asbestos in building construction materials, to eliminate future exposure to carcinogenic asbestos fibers when the building materials are disturbed.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Other international regulatory areas, often under the auspices of the UN or EU, have also initiated work on phasing out the use of fossil based fuel.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] For example, the UN's International Maritime Organization (IMO) are beginning to develop and adopt regulatory measures (MARPOL 73/78) to decarbonize international shipping.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Air quality laws may impose substantial requirements for collecting, storing, submitting, and providing access to technical data for various purposes, including regulatory enforcement, public health programs, and policy development.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Data collection processes may include monitoring ambient air for the presence of pollutants, directly monitoring emissions sources, or collecting other quantitative information from which air quality information may be deduced.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] For example, local agencies may employ a particulate matter sampler to determine ambient air quality in a locality over time.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Fossil power plants may required to monitor emissions at a flue-gas stack to determine quantities of relevant pollutants emitted.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Automobile manufacturers may be required to collect data regarding car sales, which, when combined with technical specifications regarding fuel consumption and efficiency, may be used to estimate total vehicle emissions.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] In each case, data collection may be short- or long-term, and at varying frequency (e.g., hourly, daily).
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Air quality laws may include detailed requirements for recording, storing, and submitting relevant information, generally with the ultimate goal of standardizing data practices in order to facilitate data access and manipulation at a later time.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Precise requirements may be very difficult to determine without technical training and may change over time in response to, for example, changes in law, changes in policy, changes in available technology, and changes in industry practice.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Such requirements may be developed at a national level and reflect consensus or compromise between government agencies, regulated industry, and public interest groups.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Once air quality data are collected and submitted, some air quality laws may require government agencies or private parties to provide the public with access to the information – whether the raw data alone, or via tools to make the data more useful, accessible, and understandable.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Where public access mandates are general, it may be left to the collecting agency to decide whether and to what extent the data is to be centralized and organized.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Once data are collected and published, they may be used as inputs in mathematical models and forecasts.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] For example, atmospheric dispersion modeling may be employed to examine the potential impact of new regulatory requirements on existing populations or geographic areas.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Such models in turn could drive changes in data collection and reporting requirements.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Proponents of air quality law argue that they have caused or contributed to major reductions in air pollution, with concomitant human health and environmental benefits, even in the face of large-scale economic growth and increases in motor vehicle use.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] On the other hand, controversy may arise over the estimated cost of additional regulatory standards.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Arguments over cost, however, cut both ways.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Criticisms of EPA's methodologies in reaching these and similar numbers are publicly available.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] With some industry-specific exceptions, Canadian air pollution regulation was traditionally handled at the provincial level.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] However, under the authority of the Canadian Environmental Protection Act, 1999, the country has recently enacted a national program called the Canadian Air Quality Management System (AQMS).
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] The Canadian government has also made efforts to pass legislation related to the country's greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] It has passed laws related to fuel economy in passenger vehicles and light trucks, heavy-duty vehicles, renewable fuels, and the energy and transportation sectors.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] China, with severe air pollution in mega-cities and industrial centers, particularly in the north, has adapted the Airborne Pollution Prevention and Control Action Plan which aims for a 25% reduction in air pollution by 2017 from 2012 levels.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Funded by $277 billion from the central government, the action plan targets PM2.5 particulates which affect human health.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] TA Luft is the German air quality regulation.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] The primary legislation governing air quality in India is the Air (Prevention and Control of Pollution) Act, 1981.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Additionally, the government introduced the National Clean Air Programme (NCAP) in 2019, aiming to reduce particulate matter (PM) pollution by 20-30% in at least 102 cities by 2024.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] New Zealand passed its Clean Air Act 1972 in response to growing concerns over industrial and urban air pollution.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] That Act classified sources, imposed permitting requirements, and created a process for determining requisite control technology.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Local authorities were authorized to regulate smaller polluters.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Within the Christchurch Clean Air Zone, burn bans and other measures were effected to control smog.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] The Clean Air Act 1972 was replaced by the Resource Management Act 1991.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] The act did not set air quality standards, but did provide for national guidance to be developed.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] This resulted in the promulgation of New Zealand's National Environmental Standards for Air Quality in 2004 with subsequent amendments.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] In response to the Great Smog of 1952, the British Parliament introduced the Clean Air Act 1956.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] This act legislated for zones where smokeless fuels had to be burnt and relocated power stations to rural areas.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] The Clean Air Act 1968 introduced the use of tall chimneys to disperse air pollution for industries burning coal, liquid or gaseous fuels.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] The biggest domestic impact comes from Part III, Smoke Control Areas, which are designated by local authorities and can vary by street in large towns.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] The primary law regulating air quality in the United States is the U.S.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] The law was initially enacted as the Air Pollution Control Act of 1955.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Amendments in 1967 and 1970 (the framework for today's U.S.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Clean Air Act) imposed national air quality requirements, and placed administrative responsibility with the newly created Environmental Protection Agency.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] Major amendments followed in 1977 and 1990.
[src:air-quality-law/air-quality-law] State and local governments have enacted similar legislation, either implementing federal programs or filling in locally important gaps in federal programs.
